{
  "doc_id": "59851",
  "text": "In this work, we model the temporal evolution of the turbulence prognostics such as kinetic energy, k, and its dissipation rate, ǫ, which has emerged as a common reduced system to dynamically model turbulence [CITATION_1] . Ground truth data is generated by extracting k and ǫ from a series of DNS datasets, as described in section 2. We then apply the continuous-time NODE framework to model these time series [CITATION_2] . Compared to a discrete-depth network, such as a recurrent neural network (RNN), a NODE model can learn trajectories which may be sampled at arbitrary frequencies with standard ODE solvers [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and hence is particularly well suited for physics problems.",
